then any project you take on,

00:26:31.680 --> 00:26:34.250
you don't become
obsessed by it.

00:26:34.250 --> 00:26:36.020
You may have passion for it.

00:26:36.020 --> 00:26:37.720
You may have commitment
for it.

00:26:37.720 --> 00:26:42.080
But if somebody comes in and
say, change the role, if that

00:26:42.080 --> 00:26:43.250
is the best you can do.

00:26:43.250 --> 00:26:47.090
We have seen entrepreneurs where
they start the company

00:26:47.090 --> 00:26:48.076
in Silicon Valley.

00:26:48.076 --> 00:26:50.890
You know, one guy took it
from $0 to $70 million.

00:26:50.890 --> 00:26:54.860
And then, climate person said
we need to bring in an

00:26:54.860 --> 00:26:58.440
external CEO, because, now we
are having multiple products

00:26:58.440 --> 00:27:02.280
and multiple customers, we need
different experience.

00:27:02.280 --> 00:27:02.960
Discuss it.

00:27:02.960 --> 00:27:04.972
No, I won't step down.

00:27:04.972 --> 00:27:07.450
I've built it from $0
to $70 million.

00:27:07.450 --> 00:27:09.030
What makes you think
I can't take it

00:27:09.030 --> 00:27:10.830
from $70 to $100 million.

00:27:10.830 --> 00:27:16.470
But look at your own Google
Larry Page and Brin.

00:27:16.470 --> 00:27:20.550
So if you look at it,
they started it.

00:27:20.550 --> 00:27:24.670
They brought somebody in, let
the other person run.

00:27:24.670 --> 00:27:26.570
You become an understudy.

00:27:26.570 --> 00:27:29.190
And when you think it is
right time, you come

00:27:29.190 --> 00:27:30.560
back and take it.

00:27:30.560 --> 00:27:36.450
That is called having role
clarity about when do you need

00:27:36.450 --> 00:27:41.175
to become a learner and when
do you become, what do you

00:27:41.175 --> 00:27:43.740
call, a person who
is a teacher.

00:27:43.740 --> 00:27:47.830
If you have that clarity, then
you see, even then you go

00:27:47.830 --> 00:27:52.440
home, you will not necessarily
have the Google personality.

00:27:52.440 --> 00:27:55.645
Google will become part
of your personality.

00:27:55.645 --> 00:27:57.310
It is important.

00:27:57.310 --> 00:28:01.480
Otherwise, many young people,
like Eugenics and Gen Y, when

00:28:01.480 --> 00:28:05.760
you have a clarity about what
you are contributing, where

00:28:05.760 --> 00:28:09.920
you are contributing, and what
is expected of you in terms of

00:28:09.920 --> 00:28:13.360
your contribution, you will
not get burnt out.

00:28:13.360 --> 00:28:18.970
You will have a longer passion
and a clearer set of goals.

00:28:18.970 --> 00:28:22.820
And also, your innovation
will be at the sharpest.

00:28:22.820 --> 00:28:26.720
I think that is where, I think,
the ego gets clarified

00:28:26.720 --> 00:28:30.800
without the emotion getting
too entangled with it.

00:28:30.800 --> 00:28:33.155
Think about it even in personal
relationships.

00:28:33.155 --> 00:28:33.920
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:28:33.920 --> 00:28:36.370
You made an interesting comment,
saying that sometimes

00:28:36.370 --> 00:28:39.040
you think we are more Western
than the Westerners, right?

00:28:39.040 --> 00:28:42.610
So when it comes to corporate
psyche, what do you think is

00:28:42.610 --> 00:28:44.680
the elementary difference
between the way Westerners

00:28:44.680 --> 00:28:46.700
think and the way Easterners
think?

00:28:46.700 --> 00:28:50.120
And also, why is it that you
think we don't leverage enough

00:28:50.120 --> 00:28:52.590
as Easterners from our culture,
from our values,

00:28:52.590 --> 00:28:55.640
because we are just dealing with
the onslaught of a lot of

00:28:55.640 --> 00:28:56.200
Western culture?

00:28:56.200 --> 00:28:59.020
So it would be good to see some
inputs from you on that.

00:28:59.020 --> 00:29:00.270
NAVI RADJOU: Sure.

00:29:00.270 --> 00:29:02.950
In my first book on jugaad
innovation, I tackled that

00:29:02.950 --> 00:29:06.160
topic, that essentially anybody
who would rise in

00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:09.335
Indian streets know that if you
follow the rules and drive

00:29:09.335 --> 00:29:12.330
in a very structured fashion,
you are going to die, right?

00:29:12.330 --> 00:29:15.660
So this is a culture where
essentially everything is

00:29:15.660 --> 00:29:16.230
unstructured.

00:29:16.230 --> 00:29:18.520
We operate on Indian Standard
Time, which is very different

00:29:18.520 --> 00:29:20.580
than, I know, the GMT.

00:29:20.580 --> 00:29:21.310
We all know that.

00:29:21.310 --> 00:29:22.770
So the question is--

00:29:22.770 --> 00:29:24.700
this comes literally, we were
discussing about it.

00:29:24.700 --> 00:29:26.870
It's very important observation,
because it comes

00:29:26.870 --> 00:29:28.810
back to one of the critical
attributes of wise

00:29:28.810 --> 00:29:29.940
leadership--

00:29:29.940 --> 00:29:33.790
how do you try to be authentic
and appropriate?

00:29:33.790 --> 00:29:37.020
You have to be authentic as
the Indians working in a

00:29:37.020 --> 00:29:38.000
Western company.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:41.340
So there are certain procedures,
rules, that they

00:29:41.340 --> 00:29:42.460
have to follow.

00:29:42.460 --> 00:29:44.330
That's what makes
you appropriate.

00:29:44.330 --> 00:29:46.440
But what happens is the
same way with wisdom.

00:29:46.440 --> 00:29:48.180
And that's why these two
books go hand in hand.

00:29:48.180 --> 00:29:50.290
Because ingenuity is jugaad.

00:29:50.290 --> 00:29:53.740
And wisdom is also something
that we hear about when you go

00:29:53.740 --> 00:29:55.980
to temples on the weekends or
we hear it in our families,

00:29:55.980 --> 00:29:57.410
talk about it in the evenings.

00:29:57.410 --> 00:29:59.680
But somehow both, what we
discovered, is that when

00:29:59.680 --> 00:30:02.100
people show up at 8 o'clock, 9
o'clock at work, throughout

00:30:02.100 --> 00:30:03.350
the day, we forget about it.

00:30:03.350 --> 00:30:05.545
But rather, we try to
be appropriate.

00:30:05.545 --> 00:30:07.860
We are going to follow the
corporate procedures and

00:30:07.860 --> 00:30:08.620
rules, et cetera.

00:30:08.620 --> 00:30:12.160
But if there is a way to
integrate both, that would be

00:30:12.160 --> 00:30:13.070
very powerful.

00:30:13.070 --> 00:30:14.300
And case in point is
Renault-Nissan,

00:30:14.300 --> 00:30:16.410
the French car maker.

00:30:16.410 --> 00:30:19.930
They are now coming to India
to learn about jugaad.

00:30:19.930 --> 00:30:22.520
Because they realize that they
have used what they call

00:30:22.520 --> 00:30:25.330
frugal innovation, which is they
came up with the $5,000

00:30:25.330 --> 00:30:28.200
car in France, in Europe.

00:30:28.200 --> 00:30:29.650
Now, they say, we have
to create a car

00:30:29.650 --> 00:30:31.800
which is 50% cheaper.

00:30:31.800 --> 00:30:37.820
But you cannot do that unless
you change your way you think.

00:30:37.820 --> 00:30:39.160
I love Europe.

00:30:39.160 --> 00:30:41.620
So literally, in Chennai, they
are opening a frugal

00:30:41.620 --> 00:30:44.440
engineering center out of where
they're going to create

00:30:44.440 --> 00:30:46.660
the next generation
low-cost vehicles.

00:30:46.660 --> 00:30:48.450
And the reason they are opening
it in Chennai is

00:30:48.450 --> 00:30:51.360
because out of India they think
that this unstructured

00:30:51.360 --> 00:30:55.420
way of thinking leads to
disruptive innovation.

00:30:55.420 --> 00:30:57.950
The most structured you are,
you can come up with the

00:30:57.950 --> 00:30:59.860
incremental innovation.

00:30:59.860 --> 00:31:02.420
So if they try to do a
disruptive innovation in a

00:31:02.420 --> 00:31:05.030
European context, what they will
come up with may not be

00:31:05.030 --> 00:31:06.090
disruptive.

00:31:06.090 --> 00:31:09.370
So I think one of the thing we
are hoping is that this book

00:31:09.370 --> 00:31:12.540
and my first book is basically
an attempt for Indians to take

00:31:12.540 --> 00:31:17.130
pride in what sometime
we take for granted.

00:31:17.130 --> 00:31:20.370
Or maybe, practice it in a very
kind of subconscious way.

00:31:20.370 --> 00:31:23.010
But it's so kind of fragmented,
right, because we

00:31:23.010 --> 00:31:25.210
do that in our private lives,
but we don't do that in our

00:31:25.210 --> 00:31:26.220
professional lives.

00:31:26.220 --> 00:31:29.010
So that's what my kind
of part of answer is.

00:31:29.010 --> 00:31:30.650
PRASAD KAIPA: I'll give it
from a personal side.

00:31:33.335 --> 00:31:37.900
I have been living in the United
States for 32 years.

00:31:37.900 --> 00:31:42.650
There was a time in Apple when
I had to give a presentation

00:31:42.650 --> 00:31:45.920
for John Sculley in Japan in
artificial intelligence

00:31:45.920 --> 00:31:47.540
conference.

00:31:47.540 --> 00:31:50.620
Because I was representing
John Sculley, they went

00:31:50.620 --> 00:31:54.310
through and they asked me to
go to Regis McKenna's group

00:31:54.310 --> 00:31:59.790
and spend a lot of time both
for accent reduction and to

00:31:59.790 --> 00:32:02.180
represent an American
company in Japan.

00:32:02.180 --> 00:32:05.660
And I need to be able to
represent the brand.

00:32:05.660 --> 00:32:09.700
So we went through several
days of accent reduction.

00:32:09.700 --> 00:32:12.580
They said, you know, when
I say think, I need

00:32:12.580 --> 00:32:13.950
to say it like this.

00:32:13.950 --> 00:32:16.420
But I haven't figured it out
how much I should stick my

00:32:16.420 --> 00:32:18.610
tongue out in sort of
my making myself

00:32:18.610 --> 00:32:20.545
clear to other people.

00:32:20.545 --> 00:32:22.710
Or they said, when you
use some words, you

00:32:22.710 --> 00:32:24.060
need to slow down.

00:32:24.060 --> 00:32:25.970
Indians speak so fast.

00:32:25.970 --> 00:32:27.540
NAVI RADJOU: Machine gun.

00:32:27.540 --> 00:32:30.280
PRASAD KAIPA: Like a machine
gun approach.

00:32:30.280 --> 00:32:34.300
And especially when you talk
about our organization and

00:32:34.300 --> 00:32:36.380
some of these words that have
got a completely different

00:32:36.380 --> 00:32:39.260
meaning if you are
not careful.

00:32:39.260 --> 00:32:44.620
So in that process, after
spending time with them, I

00:32:44.620 --> 00:32:48.710
gave a talk, which was like
my almost ready for talk.

00:32:48.710 --> 00:32:51.260
At that time, Regis
McKenna sat down.

00:32:51.260 --> 00:32:51.965
He came back.

00:32:51.965 --> 00:32:56.110
And he put his hand around me
and said, if you don't mind,

00:32:56.110 --> 00:32:59.350
please unlearn everything
what we taught you.

00:32:59.350 --> 00:33:02.430
We want you to go back to
your Indian accent.

00:33:02.430 --> 00:33:03.650
I said, why?

00:33:03.650 --> 00:33:07.440
They said, when you speak
with Indian accent,

00:33:07.440 --> 00:33:09.075
your eyes light up.

00:33:09.075 --> 00:33:11.310
There is intensity.

00:33:11.310 --> 00:33:13.900
And there is gesticulation.

00:33:13.900 --> 00:33:18.170
And there is you are present.

00:33:18.170 --> 00:33:20.980
When you spoke the way in which
you are supposed to

00:33:20.980 --> 00:33:24.540
speak, you represented
the brand.

00:33:24.540 --> 00:33:28.760
But the value of the brand you
represent is so bland we don't

00:33:28.760 --> 00:33:31.540
care about it.

00:33:31.540 --> 00:33:37.790
I'm suggesting to us, in the
name of becoming Western,

00:33:37.790 --> 00:33:40.620
sometimes it is like
a yin and a yang.

00:33:40.620 --> 00:33:43.075
You need to see what
is your being.

00:33:45.710 --> 00:33:48.150
Of course, you may ask, what
is this word, being?

00:33:48.150 --> 00:33:55.780
Being is like Prasad has a
certain way of being oneself.

00:33:55.780 --> 00:33:58.270
There is a way of expressing
oneself.

00:33:58.270 --> 00:34:01.920
If I want to make a lighter way
in of it, Prasad keeps on

00:34:01.920 --> 00:34:04.080
Prasad-ing.

00:34:04.080 --> 00:34:07.320
Wherever I go, it doesn't matter
whether interaction is

00:34:07.320 --> 00:34:09.449
10 minutes or 20 minutes.

00:34:09.449 --> 00:34:12.880
Who I am comes through
when I am authentic.

00:34:12.880 --> 00:34:16.040
Another way of saying being
is being authentic.

00:34:16.040 --> 00:34:18.699
And the other thing is the
doing, which is the

00:34:18.699 --> 00:34:21.280
performance.

00:34:21.280 --> 00:34:27.650
If I am actually depriving my
Indian-ness, depriving my

00:34:27.650 --> 00:34:32.170
Western-ness, depriving my
Japanese-ness, and if I try to

00:34:32.170 --> 00:34:36.270
fit in, if I try to be
appropriate, whether with my

00:34:36.270 --> 00:34:39.409
clothes, whether it is with my
accent, whether it is with my

00:34:39.409 --> 00:34:44.830
interests, then what makes me
unique and contribute to the

00:34:44.830 --> 00:34:48.040
job will be completely killed.

00:34:48.040 --> 00:34:52.600
So my ingenuity, if I take on
what my colleagues work is, it

00:34:52.600 --> 00:34:56.270
is translating creativity
into innovation,

00:34:56.270 --> 00:34:58.190
depends on your ingenuity.

00:34:58.190 --> 00:35:01.330
Indian ingenuity is
called jugaad.

00:35:01.330 --> 00:35:03.970
There is a Chinese ingenuity,
Brazilian

00:35:03.970 --> 00:35:06.830
ingenuity, American ingenuity.

00:35:06.830 --> 00:35:09.830
Some of them are represented by
Apple and Google and some

00:35:09.830 --> 00:35:10.900
of that stuff.

00:35:10.900 --> 00:35:14.490
We need to know what
is that essence.

00:35:14.490 --> 00:35:15.880
Keep the essence.

00:35:15.880 --> 00:35:18.150
Drop the rest.

00:35:18.150 --> 00:35:22.710
Then, you have an ability to
integrate East and West

00:35:22.710 --> 00:35:24.990
extraordinarily uniquely.

00:35:24.990 --> 00:35:30.970
And while you are building the
brand of your company, you are

00:35:30.970 --> 00:35:35.230
not losing the authenticity
of who you are.

00:35:35.230 --> 00:35:41.550
The wise leadership is about
being yourself while doing

00:35:41.550 --> 00:35:43.620
what needs to get done.

00:35:43.620 --> 00:35:46.160
When you do that, you are
not really enhancing

00:35:46.160 --> 00:35:47.350
your personal brand.

00:35:47.350 --> 00:35:49.920
You are actually enhancing
the corporate brand.

00:35:49.920 --> 00:35:52.460
Because the diversity
will give you

00:35:52.460 --> 00:35:54.260
different sets of ideas.

00:35:54.260 --> 00:35:58.170
And that ingenuity translates
into coming up with Indian

00:35:58.170 --> 00:36:01.730
products that may have worldwide
application because

00:36:01.730 --> 00:36:04.350
you brought your Indian
thinking into

00:36:04.350 --> 00:36:06.180
Western problem solving.

00:36:06.180 --> 00:36:09.980
I think that is where
we can be wise

00:36:09.980 --> 00:36:12.310
without losing our smartness.

00:36:12.310 --> 00:36:14.630
And I hope that's what you
can take away from this

00:36:14.630 --> 00:36:15.880
conversation.

